{"id":"2211.02381","submitter":"Fabio Rigat Dr","authors":"Fabio Rigat","title":"A Conservative Approach to Leveraging External Evidence for Effective\n  Clinical Trial Design","comments":"13 pages, 4 color figures, 2 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.ME stat.AP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  Mainstream methods for clinical trial design do not yet use prior\nprobabilities of clinical hypotheses, mainly due to a concern that poor priors\nmay lead to weak designs. To address this concern, we illustrate a conservative\napproach to trial design ensuring that the frequentist operational\ncharacteristics of the primary trial outcome are stronger than the design\nprior. Compared to current approaches to Bayesian design, we focus on defining\na sample size cost commensurate to the prior to ensure against the possibility\nof prior-data conflict. Our approach is ethical, in that it calls for\nquantification of the level of clinical equipoise at design stage and requires\nthe design to be appropriate to disturb this initial equipoise by a\npre-specified amount. Four examples are discussed, illustrating the design of\nphase II-III trials with binary or time to event endpoints. Sample sizes are\nshown to be conductive to strong levels of overall evidence, whether positive\nor negative, increasing the conclusiveness of the design and associated trial\noutcome. Levels of negative evidence provided by standard group sequential\ndesigns are found negligible, underscoring the importance of complementing\ntraditional efficacy boundaries with futility rules.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 4 Nov 2022 11:21:37 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 2 Dec 2022 09:31:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-05"}
